The paper proposes a deep learning model for detecting sleep disorders using Polysomnography (PSG) measurement channels. The model is composed of dense convolutional units (DCU) and a bidirectional long-short term memory (LSTM) layer, which are commonly used in computer vision and natural language processing tasks. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) are the most likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper uses a multi-task learning mechanism and evaluates the model performance using binary cross-entropy loss functions, which are also common in machine learning research. Hence, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) are also likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper focuses on detecting sleep disorders, which is a healthcare-related application. Therefore, cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) is a possible sub-category as well.
